article.headline: Stanford 84, UC Davis 72
article.story: STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Stanford knows it must play a lot better on both ends of the floor to keep having success once the opponents start getting tougher. Lawrence Hill had 20 points and a career-high 11 rebounds for his first double-double and Stanford beat UC Davis 84-72 on Tuesday night for its third straight victory, avenging a demoralizing defeat from last season. Fred Washington added 14 points, five rebounds and six assists and Anthony Goods had 18 points with four 3-pointers for the Cardinal (5-1), who lost 64-58 last season in Davis. Stanford won its 13th in 14 overall meetings in the series, sending the Aggies to their eighth straight road loss dating to last season. "We haven't been putting teams away. We get up big and relax or lose focus or something," Washington said. "We can't keep doing this all year. Eventually it's going to cost us a game. It didn't tonight, but down the line." UC Davis also shocked Stanford in football last year, and it was quite an embarrassment on The Farm to lose in both sports. Brook Lopez, whose twin brother Robin is Stanford's starting center, made his collegiate debut after missing the first five games while recovering from September back surgery. Brook entered the game 5:47 before halftime and played nearly four minutes before sitting down for the night. He missed the two shots he took and had one rebound. "His health is the main concern," Cardinal coach Trent Johnson said. "What we have to understand before we evaluate his perform is he has to get in game shape. He's nothing like the player he's going to be. You're talking about a young man who had back surgery. ... Don't expect him to be a world beater." Stanford, which has bounced back well from a 79-45 loss to Air Force on Nov. 15, pushed the ball in transition and looked strong on defense in its final tuneup before facing Bob Knight's Texas Tech team on Sunday in the Pete Newell Challenge down the road at San Jose's HP Pavilion. "We realize the teams we've beaten, including Denver, that we haven't played anyone except for Air Force who's a real challenge and has been playing well," Hill said. "The way we played today, (against Texas Tech) we would have lost. We need to play harder." But the Cardinal, who shot 58 percent, were outrebounded 34-31 and gave up 11 offensive rebounds. Vince Oliver scored 20 points, Rommel Marentez added 11 and Jesse Lopez Low and Thomas Juillerat had 10 apiece for winless UC Davis (0-6), which is in the final season of a four-year reclassification to Division I status. The Aggies are 0-6 to start a season for the first time since dropping their first seven games of the 1972-73 season. They will officially join the Big West Conference next season, playing non-counting games in the league this year. "We're going to have growing pains," Oliver said. "But it's encouraging not to give in. We got back in the game but it was too little too late." After Lopez Low's three-point play opened scoring, Robin Lopez blocked him on the Aggies' next possession. The Cardinal then scored 13 unanswered points as Davis went 2-for-11 with eight turnovers to start the game. Goods' third 3 of the game made it 30-15 with 8:23 left in the first half. Stanford hit 12 of its first 20 shots much to the delight of the crowd in Maples Pavilion, where a small contingent of fans from Davis made the 2-hour drive and hollered from the upper corner of the gym.
